When gentrification hits Detroit in my short lifespan, is hope the neighbourhoods of color will have the same gentrification as enclaves of white people seeking affordable housing.

Thank you so much, V-Two, for reading this post and commenting. I’m amazed that you live in such a polluted world and I wish we could import our clean air to you. I agree that people of color who stay in Detroit are perpetuating segregation, but it certainly is an attempt to stay as independent as possible.

I think wind energy and managed hydro are wonderful, but they both only work when it’s sunny or windy. And it takes a lot of power for these energy sources to create energy to run the elements that produce the energy. It wouldn’t be helpful if the bulk of it was used by the wind turbines. I like the term shanty towns being used, as it does conjure up images of the time of huts almost being thrown up. With time all of the homes would be tear downs…

I’m not sure I’m grasping your mention of wind farms only working when the wind is blowing. The grid lines carry power where it needs to go, unlike a shanty town where light poles carry power to light poles except on clear, moonlit nights.
